WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:25.800
Eu trouxe mais um caso do William Wurie, contando um exemplo exatamente sobre isso. And to the youngest son, he left a ninth of the camels. Well, three sons got into a negotiation. Seventeen doesn't divide by two.

2
00:00:26.359 --> 00:00:27.839
It doesn't divide by three.

3
00:00:28.019 --> 00:00:29.280
It doesn't divide by nine.

4
00:00:29.760 --> 00:00:31.620
Brotherly temper started to get strained.

5
00:00:32.039 --> 00:00:36.320
Finally, in desperation, they went and they consulted a wise old woman.

6
00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:39.280
The wise old woman thought about their problem for a long time.

7
00:00:39.359 --> 00:00:42.240
And finally, she came back and said, well, I don't know if I can help you.

8
00:00:42.280 --> 00:00:44.299
But at least if you want, you can have my camel.

9
00:00:45.359 --> 00:00:47.439
So then they had 18 camels.

10
00:00:47.439 --> 00:00:48.840
The first son took his half.

11
00:00:48.840 --> 00:00:50.219
Half of 18 is nine.

12
00:00:50.219 --> 00:00:51.679
The second son took his third.

13
00:00:51.679 --> 00:00:53.060
A third of 18 is six.

14
00:00:53.060 --> 00:00:54.659
The youngest son took his ninth.

15
00:00:54.659 --> 00:00:57.000
A ninth of 18 is two.

16
00:00:57.000 --> 00:00:59.219
You get 17.

17
00:00:59.219 --> 00:01:01.060
They had one camel left over.

18
00:01:01.060 --> 00:01:04.560
They gave it back to the wise old woman.

19
00:01:04.560 --> 00:01:09.739
Now, if you think about that story for a moment, I think it resembles a lot of the difficult

20
00:01:09.739 --> 00:01:11.319
negotiations we get involved in.

21
00:01:11.400 --> 00:01:14.219
They start off like 17 camels, no way to resolve it.

22
00:01:14.340 --> 00:01:18.799
Somehow what we need to do is step back from those situations, like that wise old woman,

23
00:01:19.299 --> 00:01:22.760
look at the situation through fresh eyes, and come up with an 18th camel.

24
00:01:24.359 --> 00:01:29.420
Now, finding that 18th camel in the world's conflict has been my life passion.

25
00:01:29.420 --> 00:01:32.599
I basically see humanity a bit like those three brothers.

26
00:01:32.599 --> 00:01:34.819
We're all one family.

27
00:01:34.819 --> 00:01:39.640
We know that scientifically, thanks to the communications revolution, all the tribes

28
00:01:39.640 --> 00:01:46.840
on the planet, all 15,000 tribes are in touch with each other. And it's a big family reunion.

29
00:01:46.840 --> 00:01:48.540
And yet, like many family reunions,

30
00:01:48.540 --> 00:01:50.540
it's not all peace and light.

31
00:01:50.540 --> 00:01:52.540
There's a lot of conflict.

32
00:01:52.540 --> 00:01:56.140
And the question is, how do we deal with our differences?

33
00:01:56.140 --> 00:01:58.359
How do we deal with our deepest differences,

34
00:01:58.359 --> 00:02:00.659
given the human propensity for conflict

35
00:02:00.659 --> 00:02:03.760
and the human genius at devising weapons

36
00:02:03.760 --> 00:02:05.200
of enormous destruction.

37
00:02:05.760 --> 00:02:06.799
That's the question.

38
00:02:07.620 --> 00:02:13.759
As I've spent the last better part of three decades, almost four, traveling the world,

39
00:02:14.659 --> 00:02:21.159
trying to work, getting involved in conflicts ranging from Yugoslavia to the Middle East

40
00:02:21.159 --> 00:02:25.360
to Chechnya to Venezuela, some of the most difficult conflicts on the face of the planet,

41
00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:27.780
I've been asking myself that question.

42
00:02:28.340 --> 00:02:31.680
And I think I've found, in some ways, what is the secret to peace.

43
00:02:31.719 --> 00:02:33.780
It's actually surprisingly simple.

44
00:02:34.319 --> 00:02:37.080
It's not easy, but it's simple.

45
00:02:37.560 --> 00:02:38.800
It's not even new.

46
00:02:38.900 --> 00:02:41.840
It's maybe one of our most ancient human heritages.

47
00:02:42.360 --> 00:02:44.500
The secret to peace is us.

48
00:02:44.780 --> 00:02:45.300
It's us who act as a surrounding community around any conflict, one of our most ancient human heritages. The secret to peace is us.

49
00:02:45.300 --> 00:02:48.500
It's us who act as a surrounding community

50
00:02:48.500 --> 00:02:52.620
around any conflict who can play a constructive role.

51
00:02:52.620 --> 00:02:55.479
Let me give you just a story, an example.

52
00:02:56.560 --> 00:02:58.800
About 20 years ago, I was in South Africa

53
00:02:58.800 --> 00:03:01.000
working with the parties in that conflict,

54
00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:03.680
and I had an extra month, so I spent some time

55
00:03:03.680 --> 00:03:06.259
living with several groups of San Bushmen.

56
00:03:06.819 --> 00:03:12.159
I was curious about them, about the way in which they resolved conflict because after all they're

57
00:03:12.159 --> 00:03:16.400
within living memory they were hunters and gatherers living pretty much like our ancestors

58
00:03:16.400 --> 00:03:22.240
lived for maybe 99% of the human story. And all the men have these poison arrows that they use

59
00:03:22.240 --> 00:03:26.020
for hunting. Absolutely fatal. So how do they deal with their differences?

60
00:03:26.939 --> 00:03:31.039
Well, what I learned is whenever tempers rise in those communities,

61
00:03:31.680 --> 00:03:34.719
someone goes and hides the poison arrows out in the bush.

62
00:03:35.259 --> 00:03:38.460
And then everyone sits around in a circle like this,

63
00:03:38.699 --> 00:03:41.719
and they sit and they talk and they talk.

64
00:03:41.780 --> 00:03:44.080
It may take two days, three days, four days,

65
00:03:44.080 --> 00:03:46.199
but they don't rest until they

66
00:03:46.199 --> 00:03:52.180
find a resolution or better yet a reconciliation. And if tempers are still too high, then they send

67
00:03:52.180 --> 00:03:57.900
someone off to visit some relatives. There's a cooling off period. Well, that system is, I think,

68
00:03:57.960 --> 00:04:04.360
probably the system that kept us alive to this point, given our human tendencies. That system,

69
00:04:04.360 --> 00:04:07.159
I call the third side, because if you

70
00:04:07.159 --> 00:04:11.840
think about it, normally when we think of conflict, when we describe it, there's always two sides.

71
00:04:12.319 --> 00:04:16.720
You know, it's Arabs versus Israelis, labor versus management, husband versus wife, Republicans

72
00:04:16.720 --> 00:04:22.959
versus Democrats. But what we don't often see is that there's always a third side. And the third

73
00:04:22.959 --> 00:04:26.040
side of the conflict is us. It's the surrounding community.

74
00:04:26.040 --> 00:04:28.439
It's the friends, the allies, the family members,

75
00:04:28.439 --> 00:04:29.279
the neighbors.

76
00:04:29.279 --> 00:04:32.740
And we can play an incredibly constructive role.

77
00:04:32.740 --> 00:04:36.639
Perhaps the most fundamental way in which the third side can

78
00:04:36.639 --> 00:04:40.879
help is to remind the parties of what's really at stake.

79
00:04:40.879 --> 00:04:42.720
You know, for the sake of the kids, for the sake

80
00:04:42.720 --> 00:04:44.600
of the family, for the sake of the community,

81
00:04:44.600 --> 00:04:50.079
for the sake of the future, let's stop fighting for a moment and start talking. Because the thing

82
00:04:50.079 --> 00:04:56.959
is, when we're involved in conflict, it's very easy to lose perspective. It's very easy to react.

83
00:04:56.959 --> 00:05:06.720
Human beings, we're reaction machines. And as the saying goes, when angry, you will make the best speech you will ever regret.

84
00:05:09.980 --> 00:05:10.040
And so the third side reminds us of that.

85
00:05:14.779 --> 00:05:16.579
The third side helps us go to the balcony, which is a metaphor for a place of perspective where we can keep our eyes on the prize.

86
00:05:17.300 --> 00:05:20.259
Let me tell you a little story from my own negotiating experience.

87
00:05:20.899 --> 00:05:29.000
Some years ago, I was involved as a facilitator in some very tough talks between the leaders of Russia and the leaders of Chechnya.

88
00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:32.000
There was a war going on, as you know.

89
00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:40.000
And we met in The Hague, in the Peace Palace, in the same room where the Yugoslav war crimes tribunal was taking place.

90
00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:45.060
And the talks got off to a rather rocky start when the Vice President of Chechnya

91
00:05:45.060 --> 00:05:47.339
began by pointing at the Russians and said,

92
00:05:47.740 --> 00:05:49.259
you should stay right here in your seats

93
00:05:49.259 --> 00:05:51.399
because you're going to be on trial for war crimes.

94
00:05:52.199 --> 00:05:54.100
And then he went on and he turned to me and said,

95
00:05:54.139 --> 00:05:54.899
you're an American.

96
00:05:55.399 --> 00:05:57.600
Look at what you Americans are doing in Puerto Rico.

97
00:05:58.500 --> 00:06:00.240
And my mind started racing.

98
00:06:00.420 --> 00:06:02.180
Puerto Rico, what do I know about Puerto Rico?

99
00:06:02.279 --> 00:06:03.199
I started reacting.

100
00:06:03.839 --> 00:06:07.199
But then I tried to remember to go to the balcony.

101
00:06:07.360 --> 00:06:10.060
And then when he paused and everyone looked at me for a response,

102
00:06:10.560 --> 00:06:14.240
from a balcony perspective, I was able to thank him for his remarks and say,

103
00:06:14.779 --> 00:06:16.920
I appreciate your criticism of my country,

104
00:06:16.980 --> 00:06:19.319
and I take it as a sign that we're among friends

105
00:06:19.319 --> 00:06:21.000
and can speak candidly to one another.

106
00:06:22.079 --> 00:06:25.160
And what we're here to do is not to talk about Puerto Rico or the past.

107
00:06:25.240 --> 00:06:29.980
We're here to do just to see if we can figure out a way to stop the suffering and the bloodshed in

108
00:06:29.980 --> 00:06:35.759
Chechnya. The conversation got back on track. That's the role of the third side, is to help

109
00:06:35.759 --> 00:06:41.079
the parties go to the balcony. There's an old African proverb that goes, when spider webs unite,

110
00:06:41.339 --> 00:06:48.459
they can halt even the lion. If we're able to unite our third side webs of peace, Se as espécies unirem, eles podem parar o leão. Se nós pudermos unir as espécies de paz da nossa terceira parte,

111
00:06:48.879 --> 00:06:51.860
nós podemos até parar o leão da guerra.

112
00:06:52.180 --> 00:07:28.920
Muito obrigado. FISIOS
